Kwity showed up in Week 6, reeling off three solos, four assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Paye has been a boom or bust proposition this season, with all three of his sacks coming in two of his three contests. Paye played his highest snap share since Week 2 at 58 percent and is a strong DL3 option for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against a Los Angeles Chargers team missing both of its starting offensive tackles.

Johnson flashed in Week 6, racking up four solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 63 percent of the snaps. Jermaine missed the last three weeks after suffering an ankle injury in Week 2 and was able to notch his first sack of the season against the Denver Broncos. Johnson is a high-level talent who should be treated as a top-25 option for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the Carolina Panthers. Add and start Johnson where needed.

Murphy showed up in Week 6, racking up one solo, three assists, two sacks, and one tackle for loss. Murphy is up to 3.5 sacks on the season, with at least one sack in three of his last five games. Treat Murphy as a DT1/DL3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Lawrence was excellent in Week 6, reeling off two solos, three assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. The sacks were Demarucs' first two sacks of the season. We would normally suggest a stash but a sit since this was just his second plus production outing of the year, but the Seahawks have the Houston Texans and their turnstile offensive line in Week 7, making the veteran edge a DL3 option. Add and start Lawrence where needed.

Mykel notched his first sack of the season in Week 6, finishing the afternoon with two solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 72 percent of the snaps. Tap Mykel as a DL4 option for Week 8, thanks to a plus matchup against the Houston Texans. Add and start Mykel where needed.

Eyioma was at it again in Week 6, tallying three solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss on 28 percent of the snaps. Being able to turn in a sack in back-to-back games puts Uwaszurike on the IDP map even if he is still playing a limited role. With that said, those in standard 12-team IDP leagues will just want to add him to watchlists, while those in deeper formats can consider making the stash ahead of another plus matchup in Week 7 against the New York Giants. Make the add where needed.

Laulu showed up in Week 6, racking up two solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Laulu is up to four sacks on the season, but this was his first QB takedown since back in Week 2. The sack puts Laulu back on the DL map, making him someone we can trust again as a DL3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs. Add and start Laulu as a DT1/DL3 where needed.

Brooks was at it again in Week 6, reeling off nine solos and one fumble recovery. Brooks has registered four solos in every game this year and has tallied nine or more in two of his last three outings. Count Brooks as an LB1 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Foye was excellent in Week 6, racking up six solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Oluokun has registered five or more solos in four of his last five and six or more solos in each of his last two. Fire him up as a top-10 option for what should be a busy afternoon against the Los Angeles Rams in Week 7.

Jack Campbell showed up again, tallying four solos, four assists, and one sack. Campbell has been producing at an LB1 level and is forcing us to treat him as a top-15 option until he cools down. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 7 matchup against a decimated Tampa Bay Buccaneers offense.

Jamien was excellent in Week 6, racking up six solos, seven assists, and one pass defended. Sherwood has recorded five or more solos in four of his last five, with 10 total tackles in the other. Tap him as a top-20 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

Spillane was excellent in Week 6, reeling off five solos and six assists. Spillane has re-cemented himself as one of the top IDP options at the position over the last four weeks, making his slow start seem like a distant memory. Fire him up as a top-10 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Landman continued his strong play in Week 6, racking up six solos and nine assists. The Rams linebacker has cemented himself as an elite LB2 with eight solos in two straight games. Treat him as a top-15 option for a plus matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars in Week 7.

Edge was excellent in Week 6, stacking four solos, seven assists, and one tackle for loss. Cooper has tallied four or more solos in five of his six games and has solidified himself as an elite LB2 play. Edge has slowed down a bit since his hot start, but this was his third most productive fantasy outing of the season. Start him with confidence as a top-15 option for Week 7.

Tremaine was at it again in Week 6, racking up four solos and nine assists. Edmunds had tallied six solos in his previous three and has registered four or more in four of his five contests. Treat him as a strong LB2 play for a plus Week 7 matchup against the New Orleans Saints

Devin White went off in Week 6, tallying five solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, one interception, and one pass defended. White is back in the top-15 mix after recording five or more solos in four of his six games and should be treated as such for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Singleton showed up in Week 6, tallying five solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. The Broncos linebacker has recorded four solos in five straight, and suddenly has two games with six solos in his last three. His recent production, coupled with his track record, puts him back in the LB2 mix for a tasty Week 7 matchup against the New York Giants. Start him with confidence.

Zaire finally showed up in Week 6, racking up six solos and three assists. This was Franklin's first game with more than four solos and just his second with more than three. In all honesty, Zaire is still counted as an LB2 based on name equity, as he has produced more like an LB3. Still, fire him up as a top-25 option for Week 7 as his Week 6 production is hopefully a sign of good things to come.

Lavonte was excellent in Week 6, stacking four solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. David has put together three spike weeks in his last four contests and has put himself back in the high-end LB2 mix in the process. Start him with confidence for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Cedric Gray was at it again in Week 6, tallying three solos, nine assists, and two passes defended. This was the third strong week in a row for Gray, who has seemed to settle in as an LB2 option for IDP purposes. He has a plus matchup Week 7 against New England, and should be started with confidence everywhere. Start Gray in leagues of all sizes.

Mack was excellent in Week 6, racking up six solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Wilson has tallied four or more solos in every game this season and has recorded a pass defended in five of six. Tap Mack as a top-25 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Tremaine was at it again in Week 6, racking up four solos and nine assists. Edmunds had tallied six solos in his previous three and has registered four or more in four of his five contests. Treat him as a strong LB2 play for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Dallas Cowboys.

Bush showed up in Week 6, tallying seven solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss. Devin has recorded four or more solos in five of his six games, and six or more in two of his last three. Bush is a top-25 option for Week 7, thanks to a plus Week 7 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Werner was excellent in Week 6, notching five solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Werner has recorded five or more solos in five of his six games played and should be counted as a top-15 option, especially when given plus matchups. Treat him as just that for Week 7 against the Chicago Bears.

Barrett Carter got the start in Week 6 over Logan Wilson and responded with seven solos and three assists. Carter saw additional snaps in Week 5 due to Logan Wilson's consistent issues in coverage, and the 100 percent snap share and Zac Taylor's comments suggest that this move may be permanent. Consider Carter a priority add and an LB3 with LB2 upside. Add and start Barrett where needed for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Pratt was excellent in Week 6, tallying eight solos and three assists. Pratt disappointed with the Las Vegas Raiders but managed his best fantasy output of the season in his first game with the Indianapolis Colts. Consider Germaine back in the LB2 mix until further notice. Treat him as such for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers. Add and start Pratt everywhere.

Bethune flashed in Week 6, racking up five solos and five assists in relief of Fred Warner. Tatum should see heavy snaps for the foreseeable future, if not the entire season. Treat Bethune as a priority add for deep league managers, while those in standard-size leagues should make the add where roster space allows. Treat him as an LB3 with LB2 upside for what should be a busy game against the Atlanta Falcons in Week 7.

SirVocea was excellent in Week 6, racking up six solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. Dennis has registered four or more solos in five of his six games played, and six or more in two of his last three. Tap him as an LB3 with easy LB2 upside for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Lions Week 7.

Anzalone showed up again in Week 6, reeling off seven solos and five assists. The solo count is a welcome sign as the Lions' linebacker had just seven total solos in previous three games combined. He remains a low-floor option with three games with two or fewer solos under his belt, but you can't argue with his recent production. Ride with Anzalone as an LB3/4 and start him while he's hot. Tap him as an LB3 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against an injury-ravaged Tampa Bay Buccaneers offense.

Drake was excellent in Week 6, racking up two solos, seven assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended on 97 percent of the snaps. Thomas has registered four solos in three of his past four and at least one sack in two of his last three. He has been trending upwards for the last three weeks and looks like he has finally wrestled the starting gig from Tyrice Knight. Start Drake as an LB2 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Houston Texans.

Pace was excellent in Week 5, racking up three solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Pace has recorded three or fewer solos in three of his five contests, making him more LB3 than LB2. Treat him as such despite the plus Week 7 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Shemar was excellent in Week 6, racking up six solos and five assists. Shemar got the start with Jack Sanborn sidelined with a concussion, and likely wrestled the starting job away in the process. As discussed elsewhere, Sanborn has been a liability in coverage, and Shemar has shown enough to deserve an extended look. Treat James as an LB3 with LB2 upside for Week 7 against Washington. Add and start Shemar wherever possible.

Strnad showed up in Week 6, reeling off two solos, four assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Strnad has produced in spurts but has recorded two or fewer solos in all but one game (three) this season, but has been buoyed by an impressive 3.5 sacks. His IDP value now gets murkier as Dre Greenlaw is eligible to return this week. Strnad does have Week 7 appeal due to a tasty matchup against the New York Giants, but only start him if Greenlaw is not activated from IR.

Britt was excellent in Week 6, racking up six solos and seven assists. He saw starters' snaps in Week 6 with Tyrel Dodson (concussion) sidelined and will get another start if Dodson misses another contest. Tap him as an LB3 option for Week 7 if Dodson is ruled out, thanks to a plus matchup against the Cleveland Browns. Make the speculative add where needed.

Dolac was excellent in Week 6, racking up six solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss on 45 percent of the snaps. The snaps were the first defensive snaps of the season for the UDFA rookie, who got to see the field due to Omar Spegiths being sidelined. He should see more snaps if Speights is forced to miss another contest, making him a highly intriguing speculative add in deeper leagues. Speights offers little enough (as does Troy Reeder) that the Rams could stick Dolac in the rotation permanently.

Marist showed up in Week 6, tallying four solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss, on a season high 40 percent of the snaps. Liufau is good for a splash play here or there, but is not yet fantasy relevant despite the strong Week 6. Keep him benched and look elsewhere for your Week 7 LB3/4.

Herbig stayed hot in Week 6, racking up two solos, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended on 61 percent of the snaps. Herbig is now up to 4.5 sacks on the season, with all of them coming in his last three games. Alex Highsmith has returned, but Herbig has been playing too well for Highsmith to reclaim his regular role and snap share. There is obvious risk here with Highsmith pushing Nick back to a rotational role, but Herbig played more snaps in Week 6 and should continue to see a significant role as long as he is cooking. Tap Herbig as a DL3 with DL2 upside for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Elliot kept up the strong play in Week 6, reeling off four solos and eight assists. DeShon has tallied four or more solos in each of his starts this season and should be counted as a DB2 option for a plus Week 7 matchup against Joe Flacco and the Cincinnati Bengals. Add and start Elliott where possible.

Antonie Winfield tallied five solos and four assists in Week 6, marking his first game with five or more solos all season. Winfield is playing more of a deep safety role this season, which has tanked his fantasy value, but he is still a DB2/3 option, especially during the byes. Treat him as a top-25 option for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the Detroit Lions.

Talanoa was excellent in Week 6, tallying four olos, one assist, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Hufanga has recorded four or more solos in five of his six contests and is a top-15 option during the byes. Treat him as such for a plus Week 7 matchup against the New York Giants.

Chamarri exploded in Week 6, reeling off 10 solos, four assists, and one forced fumble. Conner has tallied four or more solos in four of his six games while registering seven or more in two of them. Chamarri is a DB3 with DB2 upside for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.

Minkah showed up in Week 6, tallying five solos and two passes defended. Minkah has recorded five or more solos in each of his last two games and has tallied four or more in five of his six contests. Continue to treat him as a DB1 for a plus Week 7 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Lake was excellent in Week 6, reeling off one solo, five assists, one fumble recovery, one interception, and one pass defended. Lake has put together four plus outings in a row and is back in the DB1 mix for Week 7, thanks to a tasty matchup against the Jacksonville Jaguars. Start Lake everywhere.

Nubin was excellent in Week 6, racking up six solos and three assists. Nubin has tallied four or more solos in four of his last five contests, with this being his strongest fantasy output of the season. Rock with Nubin as a DB3 with DB2 upside for Week 7, thanks to a plus matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Geno Stone showed up in Week 6, tallying three solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Stone has recorded four or more solos in three of his six games and has registered two spike weeks on the season. Pitre exploded in Week 5, racking up three solos, one assist, two interceptions, and two passes defended vs the Cooper Rush led Baltimore Ravens.
